We are having issues with the production cloud and lists.eucalyptus.com. We have a cronjob that upload the mailman archives every 1/2 hour, and right now we are receiving the following error

{noformat}

<Error xmlns="http://s3.amazonaws.com/doc/2006-03-01/" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"><Code>EntityTooLarge</Code><Message>Your proposed upload exceeds the maximum allowed object size.</Message><Resource>pippo</Resource><RequestId>96c93078-3cc6-4db0-bcbc-90ce35df2217</RequestId></Error>

{noformat}

but the file size is 24MB. Looking at the file system on walrus, we have a lot more objects there then the one listed from s3curl. Attached here is also the ngrep on the frontend.

comments.body:
mainman.sh   test files can be found at:

{noformat}

https://github.com/eucalyptus/recipes/tree/master/bash/debian

{noformat}

The upload works with a smaller file size:

{noformat}
root@lists:/usr/local/bin# echo test > //mailman/archive.tgz
root@lists:/usr/local/bin# /usr/bin/s3curl-euca.pl --id community --put //mailman/archive.tgz -- -s http://173.205.188.6:8773/services/Walrus/mailman/mailman-archive.tgz-$(date +%d)
<PutObjectResponse xmlns="http://s3.amazonaws.com/doc/2006-03-01/" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"><PutObjectResponse><ETag>d8e8fca2dc0f896fd7cb4cb0031ba249</ETag><LastModified>2013-02-15T19:55:21.000Z</LastModified><Size>5</Size></PutObjectResponse></PutObjectResponse>root@lists:/usr/local/bin# 


{noformat}

I reduced the walrus.storagemaxbucketsizeinmb to 4MB  and I was still able to
upload a 42MB file. 

I was expecting this error:


{noformat}

public EntityTooLargeException(String entityType, String entity, BucketLogData logData)
	{
		super("EntityTooLarge", "Your proposed upload exceeds the maximum allowed object size.", entityType, entity, HttpResponseStatus.BAD_REQUEST, logData);
	}

{noformat}

I tested this as a user account ( account : eucalyptus, user jpdonnelly)

and I don't see any enforcement of limits when storagemaxbucketsizeinmb is
reduce to 4m.

